rnal entries, newspaper clippings, and accounts from the coroner’s inquest. With its penitentiary, sanatorium, pulp mill, and half-built hydro-electric dam, Boschman describes the city of Prince Albert as a “circle of pain”—one felt by white settlers but more so for the generations of First Nations and Métis people in the city and surrounding lands who were forcibly removed, incarcerated, or abducted. The harms of colonialism touched Boschman’s own family; his Cree sister Crystal was adopted by his parents during the Sixties Scoop when she was just a baby. Careful to tell his own story, not hers, Boschman accounts for his family’s own part in Canada’s shameful past. White Coal City is a poetic, necessary exploration of the painful landscapes of colonial cities in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnic relations. 0aFamilies. 0aRace relations. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh  aAlmighty Voice.  aBatoche.  aCanada.  aChurchill River.  aCree.  aDominion Survey.  aFarley Mowat.  aFirst Nations.  aGabriel Dumont.  aGreat Depression.  aGrey Owl.  aIndigenous.  aLa Colle Falls.  aLeo LaChance.  aLouis Riel.  aMaria Campbell.  aMétis.  aNesbit.  aNorth Saskatchewan River.  aPA.  aPrince Albert.  aSaskatchewan.  aSaskatoon.  aScoop.  aSouth Saskatchewan River.  aTreaty 6.  aautomobile.  acar.  achildhood trauma.  acolonialism.  across-eyed.  adrunk driving.  aenvironment.  aepigenetic.  afamily.  aheritable.  ahistory.  ahit-and-run.  ahockey.  ainherited.  aintergenerational.  ajail.  amasculinities.  amemoir.  ameridian.  apenitentiary.  aplace.  aprairies.  aracism.  aresidential school.  asettler.  atrauma.  aviolence.  avoyager.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP